<paragraph id="147EAE137082705F44016973EBA5055A" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<taxonomicName id="ECB17D908721F8038F09F1B70AD3516D" LSID="8AD950B8-0669-5C50-A49A-E60D1CD50402" authority="(L.) R. M. King &amp; H. Rob. (= Eupatorium odoratum L.)" baseAuthorityName="L.) R. M. King &amp; H. Rob. (= Eupatorium odoratum L." class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Chromolaena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Chromolaena odorata" order="Asterales" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="odorata">Chromolaena odorata (L.) R.M. King &amp; H. Rob. (= Eupatorium odoratum L.)</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2B08FC7D5032F364CE020E9297DE9FA7" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="names">
<paragraph id="31DF469C0240C9628EA5153B6E433DFD" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Names.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="15B5E09C8FFEF456EFD5C54318A38170" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="A944965A0F419E53285E9A3DE37298BB" bold="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Myanmar</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis id="6CE796D5ACF3FBB0A3852DBD2A515F6C" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">bezat</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="CEDC71BF9C54BA5E25E760CFED01ACF3" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">bizat</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="D26856D6671197F17A40216CFF0E2F76" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">jamani-chon</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="BFF29260189913DFF961F1FA32ED8366" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">taw-bizat</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="D498A146CD87C46298EE6BD9934F9E18" bold="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">English</emphasis>
: buttefly-weed, jack in the bush, siamweed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="83F03EA1C61B4DFF4CBC319077E76ED6" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="range">
<paragraph id="C2DF7BC238FE5EB16ED0281F04F7CF1D" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Range.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="FEBE4AF2C9D9571C92615A796F437810" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">New World subtropics and tropics- Florida, Texas; Mexico; and West Indies. Pantropical weed. Widespread in Myanmar.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="D837E48EB58A7D649E699D4B305AB846" pageId="24" pageNumber="25" type="use">
<paragraph id="759F15317BE2AE804C97E46D314B1282" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Use.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="44A6D2FC0D45841D31AF3EBAD426C303" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">
<emphasis id="4F9E6F5048A3CE7544B6982CAEFD6664" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="25">Leaf</emphasis>
: Used to treat dysentery.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DECC597CE48712B07274B567BD2BA251" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" type="notes">
<paragraph id="FA6EAE23B44F77A32B195724C624BD7D" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
<pageBreakToken id="866BBE7398BF2C1400231725BB0D89A1" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" start="start">Notes</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1CDF51695173DACC58D15B8DD6DCDF72" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
In India the leaf is used to treat dysentery; also applied on fresh cuts and wounds to stop bleeding (
<bibRefCitation id="80F9A0B3D2FE3223FBB2B0DE5ED231D2" author="Jain, SK" journalOrPublisher="Phytotherapy Research" pageId="173" pageNumber="174" refId="B50" refString="Jain, SK, DeFilipps, RA, 1991. Medicinal Plants of India. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc, Algonac." title="Medicinal Plants of India. 2 Vols. Reference Publications, Inc, Algonac." year="1991">Jain and DeFilipps 1991</bibRefCitation>
). The medicinal uses of this plant in the Caribbean region, as well as its chemistry, biological activity, toxicity and dosages, are discussed by 
<bibRefCitation id="7FCFFA01BBA7DDD2AC25F5F5FB736AAF" author="Germosen-Robineau, L" journalOrPublisher=".. y Tienen Faxones y Fabas Muy Diversos de Los Nuestros ... '' Origin, Evolution and Diversity of Cuban Plant Genetic Resources, Vol. 1. Institut fuer Pﬂanzengenetik und Kulturpﬂanzenforschung, Gatersleben" pageId="172" pageNumber="173" refId="B40" refString="Germosen-Robineau, L, 1997. Farmacopea Vegetal Caribena, (1st edn). Ediciones Emile Desormeaux, Fort-de-France." title="Farmacopea Vegetal Caribena, (1 st edn). Ediciones Emile Desormeaux, Fort-de-France." year="1997">
<normalizedToken id="C907C43BF87555A015271496FDF429BE" originalValue="Germosén-Robineau">Germosen-Robineau</normalizedToken>
(1997)
</bibRefCitation>
. The chemistry, pharmacology, history and medicinal uses of this species in Latin America are discussed in detail by 
<bibRefCitation id="59327CB4FF16932C62E208B4C461594A" author="Gupta, MP" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the American Oil Chemists' Society" pageId="173" pageNumber="174" refId="B42" refString="Gupta, MP, 1995. 270 Plantas Medicinales Iberoamericanas. Convenio Andres Bello (CYTED, SECAB, UNESCO), Bogota." title="270 Plantas Medicinales Iberoamericanas. Convenio Andres Bello (CYTED, SECAB, UNESCO), Bogota." year="1995">Gupta (1995)</bibRefCitation>
. A pharmacological profile including medicinal uses of this plant in Africa is given in 
<bibRefCitation id="569AA35FE767F917B8CD0D4743B876E7" author="Iwu, MM" journalOrPublisher="African Journal of Traditional, Complementary, and Alternative Medicines" pageId="173" pageNumber="174" refId="B48" refString="Iwu, MM, 1993. Handbook of African Medicinal Plants. CRC Press, Boca Raton, Florida." title="Handbook of African Medicinal Plants. CRC Press, Boca Raton, Florida." year="1993">Iwu (1993)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0AB0277A1868465EF3BEFD25E7D5AC16" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">
An aqueous ethanol extract of the leaves of 
<taxonomicName id="828814317D4E7405315F261747C44126" class="Dicotyledoneae" family="Dilleniaceae" genus="C." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="C. odorata" order="Gunnerales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="odorata">
<emphasis id="D01B552C580D6A33C4F4E64294A10E1C" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">C. odorata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were found to have antifungal activity. Chemical analysis of the extract and fractions showed the presence of biologically active constituents including some coumarines,flavonoids, phenols, tannins, and sterols. No toxic effect was noticed in the mice treated. (
<bibRefCitation id="397E88F036C5CBC80020CE4312E31D9F" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1159/000092373" author="Ngono Ngane, A" journalOrPublisher="Chemotherapy" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" pagination="103 - 106" refId="B83" refString="Ngono Ngane, A, Ebelle Etame, R, Ndifor, F, Biyiti, L, Amvam Zollo, PH, Bouchet, P, 2006. Antifungal activity of Chromolaena odorata (L.) King &amp; Robinson (Asteraceae) of Cameroon. Chemotherapy 52 (2): 103 - 106, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1159/000092373" title="Antifungal activity of Chromolaena odorata (L.) King &amp; Robinson (Asteraceae) of Cameroon." url="https://doi.org/10.1159/000092373" volume="52" year="2006">Ngono Ngane et al. 2006</bibRefCitation>
). Ethanol extracts of leaves of this species also showed antibacterial activites, inhibiting the growth of 
<taxonomicName id="747B0CC905C2085283924B6E628E273C" class="Insecta" family="Bacillidae" genus="Bacillus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Bacillus subtilis" order="Phasmida" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subtilis">
<emphasis id="0FB3AB8D7D4221A9A623903F73624F27" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Bacillus subtilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="D4C6C972A14953EF980885A77DA4E5A1" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Piperaceae" genus="Staphylococcus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Staphylococcus aureus" order="Piperales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="aureus">
<emphasis id="29E5CEE4922CD6E20416864E4E953B08" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Staphylococcus aureus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="8BB816790EB2FD11F7DCAD27B2B252EA" class="Gammaproteobacteria" family="Enterobacteriaceae" genus="Salmonella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Bacteria" lsidName="Salmonella typhimurium" order="Enterobacterales" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Proteobacteria" rank="species" species="typhimurium">
<emphasis id="EB6E2219DE1FBA974CDAB27CB5881643" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Salmonella typhimurium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The extract also was shown to reduce parasite number: antiprotozoal and cytotoxicity assays were done against 
<taxonomicName id="FB0B692BB98CA40C670AF10B16485148" class="Trichomonadea" family="Trichomonadidae" genus="Trichomonas" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Protozoa" lsidName="Trichomonas vaginalis" order="Trichomonadida" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Metamonada" rank="species" species="vaginalis">
<emphasis id="B5ED001B6090192388173402CDD5810E" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Trichomonas vaginalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DFED1949AF90C7E44FA7229D3D5895E8" class="Blastocystea" family="Blastocystidae" genus="Blastocystis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Chromista" lsidName="Blastocystis hominis" order="Blastocystida" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" phylum="Bigyra" rank="species" species="hominis">
<emphasis id="89838733ADD652B31BD0E606742BE453" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="26">Blastocystis hominis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Preliminary phytochemical screening showed the chemical compositon of the extracts to contain flavonoids, saponins, tannins and steroids (
<bibRefCitation id="DD05924C8FAAFE9AB5B4638422F030AB" author="Vital, PG" journalOrPublisher="Brazilian Journal of Medical and Biological Research" pageId="174" pageNumber="175" publicationUrl="http://www.academicjournals.org/journal/JMPR/article-full-text-pdf/BD52A2014617" refId="B137" refString="Vital, PG, Rivera, WL, 2009. Antimicrobial activity and cytotoxicology of Chromolaena odorata (L.f.) King and Robinosn and Unicaria perrottetii (A. Rich) Merr. extracts. Journal of Medicinal Plants Research 3(7): 511-518. http://www.academicjournals.org/journal/JMPR/article-full-text-pdf/BD52A2014617" title="Antimicrobial activity and cytotoxicology of Chromolaena odorata (L. f.) King and Robinosn and Unicaria perrottetii (A. Rich) Merr. extracts. Journal of Medicinal Plants Research 3 (7): 511 - 518." url="http://www.academicjournals.org/journal/JMPR/article-full-text-pdf/BD52A2014617" year="2009">Vital and Rivera 2009</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
